,Recommended,297470,28769144,"Posted: 28 December, 2016",all,Madd Matt,"Highly ambitious and promising, I havnt been this excited to see a game grow in a long time. Now is the time to buy, create your settler, and find a place in the game. It's amazing to watch this barren wilderness being settled by a growing number of player tribes, everything from trading centers to small campsites. The game world is already quite large, so I can't wait to see what the full map holds when the game exits early access.Can't recommend it enough. Have some patience during your first few hours, take the time to familiarize yourself with the different skill options and crafting menus, join one of the many tribes who go above and beyond to help new players learn and settle in, the game will suck you in.EDIT: While I am still excited for the possibilities of this game's future, some of the initial enthusiasm has died down. The devs have been worryingly inactive in the steam community and xsyon forums. Exploring further in the game world has also let me see just how much the player base has lost some major players. there are several extremely large tribes that have control over huge areas off land, have built and terraformed massive settlements, and then vanished, leaving behind these ghost settlements. While it could be cool at first to see the ""ruins"" of a lost tribe, these areas are locking down large plots of land, making them unusable for active players. even more so, many of these old super-tribes were very destructive in the way they gathered resources, meaning there are less forests, valuable junk piles have been used up, and all these resources are just sitting on these old tribes' lands, useless. On the opposite end of the spectrum but equally annoying is all the random ""tribes"" scattered around that were created by 1 player who played for 1 day then quit. these lands are also unusable for active players, often having not a single thing built on them besides the tribe totem pole.I have read elsewhere that tribes are removed if they are inactive for over 3 months. this needs changing. this is far too generous for a single-person tribe, and is useless to help against the large old tribes, which may have 200+ members gone for a year or more, but 1 person keeps logging in, which means that tribe gets to keep all that land. players should be auto-kicked from their tribe if inactive, so that way the tribe will lose that extra land and be reduced to a size that matches the actual number of active members."
