,Not Recommended,297470,31380527,Posted: 26 April,all,bozobbozo,"NOTE: just following the core of the tutorial and generally figure out the UI will take about 2 hours by itself. You may or may not come to a conclusion about it within those 2 hours; I didn't.This review is based on a measly 4 hours of play. My normal ""likes"" are Fallout 4, 7 Days to Die, Empyrion:  open-world sandbox games with a strong creative/builder component.So I should love this game, right?In a nutshell, it just wasn't fun for me. As they say, ""your mileage may vary"".  I champion thegoalof the game, but the implementation just doesn't work for me.Yes, I read the reviews that cautioned that this game is Grindy^11, but I didn't fully appreciate that. You start with a 20-slot backpack, which is already about 2/3 full with the starter stuff, and which quickly fills. You see you have slots for other containers, but you don't generally get recipes for creating them. You have to (for example) level up your basketcraft by picking about a thousand pieces of grass (I don't think this is an exaggeration), and making grass thread, grass string, grass rope, etc. until you unlock the grass container recipe.I cannot emphasize enough how DULL that is. It sounds acceptable in the abstract, but it is pretty painful.Many other sandbox/builder games, like Empyrion and 7 Days to Die, have skill unlocks and prerequisites to be able to make better things; Xsyon is a whole 'nother plane of existence in that regard.The UI doesn't help in this (or any) regard: you'll regularly need 3-4 panels open at any time to accomplish anything. That grass you're collecting? You can only hold 4 bundles at a time, and you can't for some unimaginable reason transfer it to your backpack, so you have to stop every 4 bundles and craft something with it, which of course requires several panes to be open.I ultimately, uh, sad-quit because a humanoid NPC killed me and took my starting weapon and clothes. The clothes I can replace, after a fashion; the weapon would probably take me dozens of hours to make, or have enough cash to buy.I've been waiting a long time to get into one of these types of games (along with Life is Feudal and a few others on my watchlist); I was willing to take a chance on Xsyon since it was on sale. I regret my purchase.THE GOOD:On the PvE server (Peace), the community seemed friendly and helpful, if not small.The movement controls are pretty standard. The map (there's one for PvE and one for PvP) are huge, but everywhere I went seemed very rugged and mountainous (apparently based on the Lake Tahoe area).Let me add one final note: I can see why some people enjoy this game. Building a simple hut is a major accomplishment, and you feel you've accomplished a lot in doing so; I get that, I really do. But the journey is really, really long and tedious. If you want to follow that long road, and some subset of you folks WILL enjoy it, you have my admiration."
76561198056557434,Recommended,297470,33157551,Posted: 2 July,all,zues_wolf,i like xyson.seems very challening.graphics r really good.i will recommend this to every one i know.keep up the good work and hope to see the new stuff coming out.
76561198004655782,Recommended,297470,16749143,"Posted: 27 June, 2015",all,Ichi,"I bought this game over a month ago and have not regretted making the purchase.  Please note that although my playtime record on steam is low (0.7 hours at the time of writing), it does not give a true reflection as I prefer to use the main Xsyon client - as do many other players.There are a couple of issues that I have noticed that have crept up on the forums.1) Subscription. Yes this game is a subscription based model. I know a lot feel its silly to charge a sub for this game. But actually having written in the official forums about possibilities of being free to play, the developer has actually tried testing out different pay models (including changing the sub fee). It was found that free to play created a destructive element in the game, in that it brought players who were not good for the game. Some of the players resorted to exploits, botted and even caused a lot of tension/drama in global chat by being rude/abusive (hence the reason why the majority talk in tribe chat and not global).The Cash shop idea. Wouldn't be good, Basically you are asking the developer to concentrate on making things for the cash shop rather than developing things for the game or patching bugs etc.2) It's Alpha. Well the developer has already commented on this. Basically it's on PRELUDE. So no, it not Alpha or Beta but the next step beyond that. I'm not paying to test a game. I am paying to play a game that is playable and published. Fact is that a majority of MMO's are never truly ""finished"" on release, hence why there are patches and expansions.3) Player numbers and community. Steam stats do not reflect true numbers. Majority of players still use the Xsyon client via the website as it was the default thing to do pre - steam. It's also a fact that a majority only speak in tribe chat. In the past a lot of drama was caused in global chat which became really problematic and had to be sorted out by GMs in game.The community overall is very mature and helpful. There are many vets who are happy to answer questions. Do understand though that timezone may affect peak hours for this game. I believe the majority of players are in the US/Canada timezones.Now onto the gameThe game tries to be as realistic as possible i.e. meaning you wont be able to kill bears until you have honed and got your skills really high. I believe people have high expectations from the get go and get disappointed because they cannot do the things they want to from the off. Sorry folks but this game is slower paced and longer longevity type gameplaying. Meaning be prepared to put in some hard work before expecting to be able to tackle some of the high end stuff.1) Crafting and resource gathering. Lot's to craft with many more crafting skills planned for the future.  You will need to either trade or gather resources to be able to craft. Be prepared to spend a lot of time gathering resources so you can grind your craft. Crafting and gathering also have a bonus in that each craft skill has a primary and secondary attributes. The more you use the skill, the more likely that the associated attribues with the skill will raise. For example, doing logging will increase your strength and agility. Making you a better fighter.2) Hunting and combat. Yes you can hunt stuff but you have to start off small i.e rats and chickens. You also need to locate them first before being able to kill them. After you kill critters, you can improve your hunting skills by skinning, gutting, decapitating etc. Don't expect to move up quickly as it will take a while to climb up the hunting ladder. There are also zombies called Revenants. Do not mistake these for players. If they kill you, they take your gear and use it. So for every critter that kills a player, they ""grow"" and increase in strength.3) Thirst and Hunger. Yes you have to manage these. You can fish, forage or farm for food to eat. For thirst you can drink from rivers or fill and carry a waterpouch with you. There is a balance though as overindulging will give you penalties. Become hungry or thirsty and you don't regenerate health and energy. You can die from prolonged thirst and hunger just like in real life.4) Health, Energy and Encumbrance. All of these can be improved as you keep grinding the associated skills. For instance grinding on a skill that increases your strength will help improve the amount you can carry and therefore your encumbrance levels.Health is self explanatory. When it reaches zero, your dead.Energy is basically like stamina. When you perform actions, it uses stamina. For example you can only sprint when you have more than 50% Energy. Once it reaches 50% or less, then you can no longer sprint, just light jog. When you run out of energy you have to rest or stop your action.Encumbrance levels is your carrying capacity. Basically if you are carrying a lot if items, it will be harder to run and uses more energy doing so. One of the ways to make this less of a problem is by using a cart to transport goods.Death has no real penalties at present.5) Tribes. I was lucky to find a nice tribe. Personally I think it's helpful to get into a tribe early on. You can solo but expect to work a lot more. Tribes give you an advantage in that they can give you tools and food so you do not have to worry about it and can concentrate on your skills. Also having someone to give you advice or answer your questions is nice to have. Also large scale building projects is very demanding and much more easier to complete within a tribe and fun too!Like I said I'm still having fun but it's not a game for everyone. The game requires patience and work before you see any progress  - just like in real life. People who have high expectations of being uber in the least amount of time and effort need not apply!I wish people would try the game and give it a chance before turning a blind eye to it. You never know, you might enjoy yourself."
